<TITLE> Tunisia upholds death sentence on coup suspect </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TUNIS, Feb 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A Tunis court upheld a death sentence on Wednesday against an Islamist found guilty of attempting to overthrow the secular-minded government in a case that has attracted wide attention in north Africa. Saber Ragoubi, one of 30 men arrested after they engaged police in gunfights just over a year ago, would be the first person to be executed in Tunisia since 2000, although he has the right to further appeal. The court commuted another death sentence on Imed ben Ameur to life imprisonment, judge Manoub Hmidane said. Life sentences on two suspected accomplices -- Oussama El Abadi and Mohamed Beltifa -- were cut to 30 years and 20 years respectively. Prison terms for 27 others were mostly unchanged. Fourteen gunmen were killed in the fighting, which took place in December 2006 and January 2007. The clashes, rare in a country known to most Europeans as a sleepy tourist destination, raised fears that a loose network of militants was stepping up attempts to topple governments in the Maghreb. In December the court found the 30 men guilty of belonging to a terrorist group, disturbing public order and acquiring illegal military training. The defendants denied the charges and said they had made confessions because they had been beaten. In its initial ruling, the court handed out two death sentences, sentenced eight men to life in prison, seven others got 30 years in jail and the other 13 were handed prison terms of between five and 20 yea
